"Walther G.-R.","Weakening of climatic constraints with global warming and its consequences for evergreen broad-leaved species",2002,"Folia Geobotanica","37","1",,"129","139",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036074651&partnerID=40&md5=692f78c13403003835cbdf4f58a04f00","Institute of Geobotany, University of Hannover, Nienburger St. 17, Hannover D-30167, Germany","Walther, G.-R., Institute of Geobotany, University of Hannover, Nienburger St. 17, Hannover D-30167, Germany","Meteorological stations located in the lower areas of southern Switzerland have recorded a period with distinct milder winter conditions since 1970 as compared with the first half of the 20th century. The twofold set of climatic parameters, the absolute values and frequency of minimum temperatures as well as the length of the growing season have shifted towards warmer conditions in the last thirty years. In this paper, consequences of the lengthened growing season to 11 months are discussed. The detected climatic change supposedly favours species with evergreen broad-leaved growth form. With the analysis of 170 resurveyed relevés the hypothesis of whether the group of evergreen broad-leaved species have succeeded in profiting from this weakening of climatic constraints was verified. Conspicuous changes have been observed not only in terms of the abundance and frequency of indigenous evergreen broad-leaved species, but also with a number of exotic species sharing equal characteristics and having succeeded in colonizing forest areas and establishing stands in the shrub layer. It is suggested that in areas with a minimum temperature above - 10 °C and sufficient water supply throughout the year, evergreen broad-leaved species become increasingly competitive as soon as the growing season (days without frost) lengthens to about 300-320 days.","Climate and vegetation; Climate change; Growth forms; Species range","broad-leaved forest; climate change; evergreen forest; geographical distribution; global change; growing season; growth form; Switzerland",,,,,,"Antonietti, A., The forest associations on carbon rich soils of the submontane belt in the Canton Ticino (1968) Mitt. Eidgenössischen Anst. Forstl. Versuchwesen, 4, pp. 88-221; Aschwanden, A., Beck, M., Häberli, C., Haller, G., Keine, M., Roesch, A., Sie, R., Stutz, M., Klimatologie der Schweiz (Jahrgang 1996). Klimatologie 1961-1990, Heft 2 (1/4). Bereinigte Zeitreihen (1996) Die Ergebnisse des Projektes Klima 90: Auswertungen, 1. , SMA, Zürich; Box, E.O., (1981) Macroclimate and Plant Forms: An Introduction to Predictive Modelling in Phytogeography, , Tasks for Vegetation Science, Junk Publishers, The Hague; Braun-Blanquet, J., (1964) Pflanzensoziologie, , Springer Verlag, Wien; Brown, J.L., Li, S.-H., Bhagabati, N., Long-term trend toward earlier breeding in an American bird: A response to global warming? (1999) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 96, pp. 5565-5569; Carraro, G., Klötzli, F., Walther, G.-R., Gianoni, P., Mossi, R., Observations of changes in vegetation in relation to climate warming (1999) Final Report NRP 31, , vdf, Zürich; Chapin F.S. III, Bret-Harte, M.S., Hobbie, S.E., Zhong, H., Plant functional types as predictors of transient responses of arctic vegetation to global change (1996) J. Veg. Sci, 7, pp. 347-358; Delarze, R., Gonseth, Y., Galland, P., (1999) Lebensräume der Schweiz, , Ott, Thun; Diaz, S., Cabido, M., Plant functional types and ecosystem function in relation to global change (1997) J. Veg. Sci, 8, pp. 463-474; Dierschke, H., (1994) Pflanzensoziologie, , UTB, Ulmer, Stuttgart; Ellenberg, H., Rehder, H., Natürliche Waldgesellschaften der aufzuforstenden Kastanienflächen im Tessin (1962) Schweiz. Z. Forstwesen, 113, pp. 128-142; Gianoni, G., Carraro, G., Klötzli, F., Thermophile, an laurophyllen Pflanzenarten reiche Waldgesellschaften im hyperinsubrischen Seenbereich des Tessins (1988) Ber. Geobot. Inst. ETH, Stiftung Rübel, 54, pp. 164-180; Grabherr, G., Gottfried, M